SIMPLE: roam
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Roam
<hw>Roam</hw> <pr>(r⟦omac⟧m)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Roamed</conjf> <pr>(r⟦omac⟧md)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. &
vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Roaming</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE.
<ets>romen</ets>, <ets>ramen</ets>; cf. AS. <ets>⟦amac⟧r⟦aemac⟧man</ets>
to raise, rise, D. <ets>ramen</ets> to hit, plan, aim, OS.
<ets>r⟦omac⟧m⟦omac⟧n</ets> to strive after, OHG. <ets>r⟦amac⟧men</ets>.
But the word was probably influenced by <ets>Rome</ets>; cf. OF.
<ets>romier</ets> a pilgrim, originally, a pilgrim going to Rome, It.
<ets>romeo</ets>, Sp. <ets>romero</ets>. Cf. <er>Ramble</er>.]</ety>
<def>To go from place to place without any certain purpose or direction;
to rove; to wander.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He <qex>roameth</qex> to the carpenter's house.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Daphne <qex>roaming</qex> through a thorny wood.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To wander; rove; range; stroll; ramble.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Roam</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Roam
<hw>Roam</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To range or wander over.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And now wild beasts came forth the woods to <qex>roam</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Roam</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Roam
<hw>Roam</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The act of roaming; a wandering; a
ramble; <as>as, he began his <ex>roam</ex> o'er hill and
dale</as>.</def> <rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Roamer</ent>⟦br⟧
